Web scraping with R

Part 2: Scraping across multiple pages

Jason Grafmiller

31 December, 2020

This is part 2 (part 1 and part 3) of a series of tutorials on web scraping in R. If you are new to web scraping, please see the first part before continuing. In this tutorial, well see how to scrape information from multiple pages on a single site.

Setup

Load in the R libraries youll need for this tutorial. As usual, well be using the {rvest} package, which is a fantastic resource created by Hadley Wickham, the creator of the tidyverse.

library(tidyverse, quietly = T) # for convenient data wrangling and styling
library(tictoc) # for timing processes
library(tidytext) # for text mining
library(rvest)

For this tutorial well be creating a custom corpus of quotes from the Quotes to Scrape website. Like last time, this is a freely available site designed to help learn how to scrape. So we know there are no issues with using it :)

This page has a simple setup with a list of quotes and their authors, along with some tags.

Quotes to Scrape page

Fortunately, scraping across multiple pages is fairly easy. After a little searching online, I turned up this helpful discussion. The code below is modelled on the ideas in that discussion thread.

Scraping the first page

Well start by scraping the quote information from the first page and then see how to repeat this process across all the pages on the site. Well use read_html() to read in the main page.

quotes_main_url <- "https://quotes.toscrape.com/"

quotes_main_page <- read_html("https://quotes.toscrape.com/")

Now we want to find the right selector for our quotes. Here we want to be a bit careful, because in this case we want not only the quote text, but also the author and tags. So we want to make sure we highlight the entire quote box, like so:

Quote boxes highlighted with Selector Gadget

We can see that the quote box selector is .quote (recall this refers to the class quote). Nice and simple! Next well create a vector of the quote nodes with html_nodes().

quote_nodes <- quotes_main_page %>% 
  html_nodes(".quote")

head(quote_nodes)
{xml_nodeset (6)}
[1] <div class="quote" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/CreativeWork">\n ...
[2] <div class="quote" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/CreativeWork">\n ...
[3] <div class="quote" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/CreativeWork">\n ...
[4] <div class="quote" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/CreativeWork">\n ...
[5] <div class="quote" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/CreativeWork">\n ...
[6] <div class="quote" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/CreativeWork">\n ...

These are a bit more complex than in the first tutorial. The issue is that these quote nodes themselves comprise multiple different component parts. Recall that HTML (and XML) have embedded structure, where any single node may contain multiple child nodes. We can find the children of a node like so.

# The child nodes of the first quote node in our vector of nodes
quote_nodes[1] %>% 
  html_children()
{xml_nodeset (3)}
[1] <span class="text" itemprop="text">The world as we have created it is a  ...
[2] <span>by <small class="author" itemprop="author">Albert Einstein</small>\ ...
[3] <div class="tags">\n            Tags:\n            <meta class="keywords" ...

So each node of class quote (which is denoted in CSS by .quote) contains three children. Poking around with Selector Gadget in your browser, you should be able to identify the selectors of relevant subparts of each quote node. Selector Gadget is particularly useful for finding the tag selectors, which is actually a slightly more complex selector .tags .tag. This in fact denotes a node of class tag whose parent node is of class tags.

If we do so, we learn the following.

  • Quote text is denoted with the selector .text
  • Quote author is denoted with the selector .author
  • Individual quote tags are denoted with the selector .tags .tag

Now that we have these, we can start scraping our quotes

Get quote info

Before we start, well create an empty list that well use to store our quote information as we go through each node.

quote_list <- vector("list")

The reason we do it this way (as opposed to starting with an empty dataframe) is that we dont know how many quotes we have, and this method is much more efficient in R. Its negligible in this instance, but in other real cases with hundreds or thousands of nodes and pages, small differences in efficiency can add up. Plus, I like to encourage best practices in more efficient programming :)

Note: By far the fastest way to do this would be to create a dummy dataframe of N rows, where N = the number of quotes (or other observations) we have, and then replace each dummy row with the requisite info for each quote. If you really want to geek out on this, see this post on efficiency analysis of different accumulation procedures in R. Of course, if we were really concerned about efficiency wed be using {data.table}, but thats another tutorial of its own

Anyway, we loop through our vector of nodes, pull out the text, author and tag information, and store that as a list inside our quote_list.

for(i in seq_along(quote_nodes)){
  # Get current node
  node <- quote_nodes[i]
  # Get current node's text
  quote <- node %>% 
    html_nodes(".text") %>% 
    html_text() %>% 
    str_replace_all("(|)", "") #remove the unnecessary quote characters
  # Get current node's author
  author <- node %>% 
    html_nodes(".author") %>% 
    html_text()
  # Get current node's tags
  tags <- node %>% 
    html_nodes(".tags .tag") %>% 
    html_text() %>% 
    paste(collapse = "; ") # collapse tags into one string, separated by ';'
  # Add to the list
  quote_list[[i]] <- list(quote = quote, author = author, tags = tags)
}

Now we can create a quote dataframe from our list with bind_rows().

quote_df <- bind_rows(quote_list)
quote_df

Simple!

Scraping multiple pages

So we have the first page, but what about the rest? You should be able to see that you can click on the Next button and go to more pages of quotes. If you keep clicking, eventually youll get to the end at the 10th page. So how do we get the quotes on all these other pages?

There are several ways we could do this, but I think the simplest method is to look at the url of the different pages themselves, and use those. So if you go to the first page (the main page), the url is https://quotes.toscrape.com/. But if you go to the subsequent page(s), you see that they have the basic url formula, where the url for each page is identical to the main page, except for the addition of page/??/, where the ?? is number of the page. So we can use this to create a list of page urls like so.

page_urls <- vector()

for(i in 1:10){
  if (i == 1){
    url <- "https://quotes.toscrape.com/"
  } else {
    url <- paste("https://quotes.toscrape.com/page/", i, "/", sep = "")
  }
  page_urls[i] <- url
}

page_urls
 [1] "https://quotes.toscrape.com/"        
 [2] "https://quotes.toscrape.com/page/2/" 
 [3] "https://quotes.toscrape.com/page/3/" 
 [4] "https://quotes.toscrape.com/page/4/" 
 [5] "https://quotes.toscrape.com/page/5/" 
 [6] "https://quotes.toscrape.com/page/6/" 
 [7] "https://quotes.toscrape.com/page/7/" 
 [8] "https://quotes.toscrape.com/page/8/" 
 [9] "https://quotes.toscrape.com/page/9/" 
[10] "https://quotes.toscrape.com/page/10/"

Next we simply loop through our pages, and for each page, we extract the quote nodes then loop through these to get the quote information, which we store to a list. Before we do this, well create an empty list that will store our dataframes of quotes from each page (so well have a list of dataframes).

main_quote_list <- vector("list")

Begin scraping

tic()
for(i in seq_along(page_urls)){
  # Get current url
  url <- page_urls[i]
  # Create a new list for current page
  quote_list <- vector("list")
  # Get the nodes from the current page
  quote_nodes <- read_html(url) %>% 
     html_nodes(".quote")
  # Now loop through the current page's nodes, get the text, author and tags,
  # and save this to the quote_list. This is the code we created above
  for(j in seq_along(quote_nodes)){
    # Get current node
    node <- quote_nodes[j]
    
    quote <- node %>% 
      html_nodes(".text") %>% 
      html_text() %>% 
      str_replace_all("(|)", "") #remove the unnecessary quote characters
    
    author <- node %>% 
      html_nodes(".author") %>% 
      html_text()
    
    tags <- node %>% 
      html_nodes(".tags .tag") %>% 
      html_text() %>% 
      paste(collapse = "; ") # collapse tags into one string, separated by ';'
    # Add to the list
    quote_list[[j]] <- list(quote = quote, author = author, tags = tags)
  }
  # Now add the current page's quote info, as a dataframe, to the main_quote_list
  main_quote_list[[i]] <- bind_rows(quote_list)
}

# Finally, we convert our main_quote_list to a dataframe
main_quote_df <- bind_rows(main_quote_list)
toc()
6.79 sec elapsed

Note: When Im working on processes that involve lots of steps and/or repeated actions, I like to time the processes so I have an idea of how long different things take. The {tictoc} package is great for this. Even processes that run seemingly fast individually can add up very quick. A four-second process may seem like a short amount of time, but if you have to repeat that process 1000 times it will take over an hour to finish. If you can estimate your time for a single iteration, you can get a sens of how long the full analysis might take, then you can save heavy processing tasks to run at off times (e.g.overnight).

Now check to see if it worked.

main_quote_df

Cool. Dont forget to save the dataframe for later use.

saveRDS(main_quote_df, "data_raw/main_quote_data.rds")

Doing stuff with our quotes

Now that we have the full set of quotes, we can do all kinds fo fun things, e.g.see who the most frequently quoted person is on this page.

main_quote_df %>% 
  count(author, sort = TRUE)

Or we can see what the most common tags are using unnest_tokens() from tidytext.

main_quote_df %>% 
  unnest_tokens(tag, tags) %>% 
  count(tag, sort = TRUE)

We can create a word cloud of these if we like.

library(ggwordcloud)
library(viridis)

main_quote_df %>% 
  unnest_tokens(tag, tags) %>% 
  count(tag, sort = TRUE) %>% 
  ggplot() + 
  geom_text_wordcloud_area(
    aes(label = tag, size = n, color = n)) +
  scale_size_area(max_size = 16) +
  scale_color_viridis()

We could count the words in the quotes

main_quote_df %>% 
  mutate(
    n_words = str_count(quote, '\\w+')
  )

Or count the wordiness of different authors by taking the ratio of words to quotes.

number_of_quotes <- main_quote_df %>% 
  count(author, name = "n_quotes")

number_of_words <- main_quote_df %>% 
  unnest_tokens(word, quote) %>% 
  count(author, name = "n_words")

author_df <- number_of_quotes %>% 
  inner_join(number_of_words) %>% 
  mutate(
    wordiness = n_words/n_quotes
  )

author_df %>% 
  filter(n_quotes > 1) %>% # look at authors with more than one quote
  arrange(desc(wordiness))
